	<text id="ruskin_to_mother_july_15_1867">
	    
	    <header>
	        <inventNo>1996L00316</inventNo>
	    </header>
	
	    <body>
	        <div type="text">
	            <pb n="1"/>           
	            <opener>
	                <placeName><!-- match letter exactly, delete if unnecessary -->
	                    <rs key="Q1017196" type="place">Wigtown,</rs>
	                </placeName>
	                <day>Monday Morning,</day>
	                <date when="1867-07-15"><!-- match letter exactly, delete if unnecessary -->
	                    <rs type="date">15th July, 1867.</rs>
	                </date>
	                <salute>My dearest <rs key="47637407" type="person">Mother</rs>,</salute><!-- match letter exactly, delete if unnecessary -->
	            </opener>
	            
	            <p id="p1">
	                <s id="s1">Their posts are so awkward here that I am pretty sure to miss the one at <rs key="Q192896" type="place">Carlisle</rs>, so this is to enclose your to-morrow's envelope and to say, I called on <rs key="miss_mcadam" type="person">Miss McAdam</rs> <rs key="mrs_young" type="person">Mrs. Young's</rs> niece yesterday, and was much pleased by her gentle face and beautiful manner.</s>
	                <s id="s2">The Scottish real ladies of the middle classes of <rs key="Q21" type="place">England</rs>, or perhaps more accurately, the Scottish aristocracy is a much larger body than the English, though the greater part of it untitles.</s>
	                <s id="s3">The <rs key="evergreens" type="flora">evergreens</rs> in her <pb n="2"/> garden were planted by <rs key="mrs_young" type="person">Mrs. Youngs</rs> and are now beautiful - not having suffered at all by last spring's frost.</s>
	            </p>    
	
	            <p id="p2">    
	                <s id="s4">I called also in my old uncle <rs key="uncle_tweeddale" type="person">Tweeddale's</rs> house, on <gap reason="illegible" unit="words" quantity="2"/> Lane - I am pleased with <rs key="a_simson" type="person">Arbuthnot</rs> who is to marry <rs key="k_simson" type="person">Kate</rs>: and very much pleased indeed with his family, especially his sister and her husband.</s>
	            </p>    
	
	            <p id="p3">    
	                <s id="s5">I hear excellent accounts of the one who has engaged <rs key="m_agnew" type="person">Mary</rs>.</s>
	                <s id="s6">The Procurator Fiscal of <rs key="Q652035" type="place">Dumfries</rs> must be a very good position.</s>
	                <s id="s7"><rs key="m_agnew" type="person">Mary</rs> herself <pb n="3"/> is a far nicer and more intelligent girl than I supposed.</s>
	                <s id="s8"><rs key="k_simson" type="person">Kate</rs> is very good too, and much improved happiness.</s>
	            </p>    
	
	            <p id="p4>">    
	                <s id="s9">I have been quite comfortable without <rs key="f_crawley" type="person">Crawley</rs>, but must go now to <rs key="Q1025076" type="place">Keswick</rs> to get put to rights in portmanteau</s>
	            </p>
	            
	            <closer>
	                <salute>Ever my dearest <rs key="47637407" type="person">Mother</rs>, Your most affectionate Son,</salute><!-- optional - delete if unnecessary -->
	                <signed><!-- optional - delete if unnecessary -->
	                    <rs key="73859585" type="person">J. Ruskin.</rs>
	                </signed>
	             </closer>
	        </div>
	    </body>
	</text>      
	
